Featurization, Model Selection and Tuning Project Solution¶

DOMAIN: Semiconductor manufacturing process

CONTEXT: A complex modern semiconductor manufacturing process is normally under constant surveillance via the monitoring of signals/variables collected from sensors and or process measurement points. However, not all of these signals are equally valuable in a specific monitoring system. The measured signals contain a combination of useful information, irrelevant information as well as noise. Engineers typically have a much larger number of signals than are actually required. If we consider each type of signal as a feature, then feature selection may be applied to identify the most relevant signals. The Process Engineers may then use these signals to determine key factors contributing to yield excursions downstream in the process. This will enable an increase in process throughput, decreased time to learning and reduce the per unit production costs. These signals can be used as features to predict the yield type. And by analysing and trying out different combinations of features, essential signals that are impacting the yield type can be identified.

DATA DESCRIPTION: sensor-data.csv : (1567, 592) The data consists of 1567 datapoints each with 591 features. The dataset presented in this case represents a selection of such features where each example represents a single production entity with associated measured features and the labels represent a simple pass/fail yield for in house line testing. Target column 1 corresponds to a pass and 1 corresponds to a fail and the data time stamp is for that specific test point.

PROJECT OBJECTIVE: We will build a classifier to predict the Pass/Fail yield of a particular process entity and analyse whether all the features are required to build the model or not.

In [144]:
for col in df_copy:
  # Calculate the percentage Null value for column
  null_prcnt = (df_copy[col].isnull().sum()/len(df_copy))*100
  # Drop the feature that has more than 20% NULL values present in them
  if null_prcnt >= 20 :
    df_copy = df_copy.drop(col, axis=1)
  # Rest cases, impute with mean value of the feature
  elif null_prcnt != 0 :
    df_copy[col]= df_copy[col].fillna(df_copy[col].mean())

# Replace the outliers with median
for i in df_corr.columns:
  q1 = df_corr[i].quantile(0.25)
  q3 = df_corr[i].quantile(0.75)
  iqr = q3 - q1    
  low = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
  high = q3 + 1.5 * iqr
  df_corr.loc[(df_corr[i] < low) | (df_corr[i] > high), i] = df_corr[i].median()

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score,confusion_matrix,precision_score,recall_score,f1_score,classification_report

# Evaluating classifier performance
def evaluate_model_perf(model_descr, x, x_pred, y, y_pred):
  print('-'*40)
  print("Classification report:")
  print(classification_report(y,y_pred)) 
  print('-'*40)
  print('\nTraining Data Accuracy Score:\t{:.2f} '.format(accuracy_score(x,x_pred)))
  print('\nTest Data Accuracy Score:\t{:.2f} '.format(accuracy_score(y,y_pred)))
  print('\nPrecision:\t\t\t{:.2f} '.format(precision_score(y,y_pred, average='macro')))
  print('\nRecall:\t\t\t\t{:.2f} '.format(recall_score(y,y_pred, average='macro')))
  print('\nF1 Score:\t\t\t{:.2f} '.format(f1_score(y,y_pred, average='macro')))
  print('-'*40)
  print("\nConfusion Matrix:")
  print(confusion_matrix(y,y_pred))
  print('-'*40)
  

  # performance_matrix list of this model
  performance_matrix = []
  performance_matrix.append(model_descr)
  performance_matrix.append(accuracy_score(x,x_pred)*100)
  performance_matrix.append(accuracy_score(y,y_pred)*100)
  performance_matrix.append(precision_score(y,y_pred, average='macro')*100)
  performance_matrix.append(recall_score(y,y_pred, average='macro')*100)
  performance_matrix.append(f1_score(y,y_pred, average='macro')*100)
  # Store the performance per model
  model_comparision_list.append(performance_matrix)

def display_model_matrix():
  final_perf_df = pd.DataFrame(model_comparision_list, columns=['Model','Train Accuracy','Test Accuracy', 'Precision','Recall','F1 Score'])
  final_perf_df.sort_values(by=['F1 Score'], inplace=True, ascending=False)

  print('-'*80)
  print("Model Performance Comparision Matrix")
  print('-'*80)
  print(final_perf_df)
  print('-'*80)

B. Select the final best trained model along with your detailed comments for selecting this model.

Final Model Selection Analysis:

  1. DecisionTree Base, SVC Base, GradBoosting Base, AdaBoost Base and RandForest Base seem to be overfit model as train accuracy is 100%. So we will skip them.

  2. RandForest Best Params + PCA and RandForest Best Params both are almost overfitting model. Skip them.

  3. Next best model seems to be AdaBoost Best Params + PCA with 94% train Accuracy, 85% test accuracy. The variance is also not much and fares well at F1 score. For our classification problem, we need to strike a balance between precision and recall. Hence F1 score is of importance here.

Let us go with AdaBoost Best Params + PCA model as our final model. This also requires only 14 features to predict.

####################### Pickle the Final model for future prediction ##########################
# Save the Model to file in the current working directory
def save_pickle(classifier):
  best_classifier_file = "Pickle_ADA_Model.pkl"  
  with open(best_classifier_file, 'wb') as file:  
    pickle.dump(classifier, file)
  return best_classifier_file

# Load the Model back from file
def load_pickle(best_classifier_file):
  with open(best_classifier_file, 'rb') as file:  
    Pickle_ADA_Model = pickle.load(file)
  print(Pickle_ADA_Model)

# Save best classifier as pickle file
final_model_file = save_pickle(final_model)

# Load for verification Purpose
load_pickle(final_model_file)

D. Write your conclusion on the results.

Conclusion:

  1. Aim of the project was to identify both True Positives and True Negatives to the maximum level. Hence recall score is important. But if we only focus on recall and improve the score, then precision would go down. This leads to identifying more of Actual Pass as Fails. So, the ideal metric to look into is F1 score which will aim on reducing both False Negative an False Positives.

  2. We had 93.36% (1463) of pass class and only 6.63% (104) of fail class. An Oversampling or SMOTE or Downsampling will not help here. Downsampling leads to a loss of data which leads to reduction in variance of class 1 and oversampling leads to creating a duplicate or SMOTE synthetic oversampling data. This data will not be a normal distribution data and if a data is not normally distributed we will not be able to analyze and come to a conclusion. Recommendation is to gather more of failed data input.

  3. The model that best performed was Ada Boost Classifier as explained earlier. The inputs were scaled, reduced in dimensionality using PCA to 14 features from massive 592 features. The inputs used for training were SMOTE balanced.

  4. Final model has been pickled for further use.
